title: For Sale:  Black Powder Collection - Varied Armaments for Sale - Rifles, Pistols, Cannon
postcontent:
Hello Armslist,



        I have a few odd duckling black powder guns that don't fit with my standard calibers, so I'm putting them up for sale. They've all been awesome to shoot, but I just don't have room for dozens of different kinds of ammunition and powder.


    First, I have my pride and joy; a CVA Hawken Percussion Rifle, .54 Caliber with iron sights and ramrod. Also included is roughly 100 .54 balls, as well as roughly 100 percussion caps. This gun is pretty but has some dings and normal wear-and-tear from my hunting trips. The picture shows my brass Hawken; the grip is steel(or painted brass) on this one. Asking price: $320

    Next, I have a Jukar Percussion Pistol, .45 Caliber with iron sights and ramrod. Also included is small powder horn on a leather strap, still about half full of FFFFg powder. Asking price: $140.00


    There are two Pietta revolvers, all brand-new, never-fired. Pictures will follow soon, but you can feel free to google them, as they are all new in the box. Details:

-1858 New Army Remington, Steel Frame, .44 cal                              -     $320
-1858 New Army Remington, Stainless Steel, .44 cal                           -     $420



      These are beautiful revolvers, brand new in their boxes with all the paperwork, and can be had without an FFL transfer, as they are technically 'antiques' instead of 'firearms' under BATFE regulations. Once you pick one up, all you need is some powder, shot and wadding, and you're ready for the range. These revolvers, unlike their original counterparts, are rifled for better accuracy. I personally love that Pietta does this; it makes hitting a man-sized target possible past 20 yards, unlike the true 'smoothbore' revolvers. I highly recommend 'baby pumpkins' as the best targets this time of year. They explode quite dramatically when a lead ball zips through them.


     I also have a small 1-pounder 'frontier cannon'. Barrel was cast in 2001. Slight surface rust along muzzle area, but nothing to worry over. The carriage is pretty rough; it was a stop-gap measure until we completed the sleigh carriage that these cannon were originally coupled with. But this little beauty will launch a solid shot over a hill, or mulch a piece of plywood with a canister round. Aside from my Parrott Rifled cannon, this one has been by far the most fun to shoot. In terms of scale, the barrel is 4ft long, bore diameter is 1 3/8"; this cannon is the type you would have found on Lewis & Clark's launches, or really any trading launches throughout the 19th century, to give them an added advantage over the native populations. The weld marks are still visible, I work on grinding them down and removing surface rust almost daily. Asking price: $340.00


        Finally, a small derringer from the 1850's, created somewhere in London. The markings have been worn down significantly so it's hard to tell, this information is from a professional appraisal. It is the third pistol down, in the third picture. Asking price: $180.00


     Keep an eye on this ad; I have several un-appraised pistols and rifles that will be up as soon as I have them professionally appraised. And I am always trading and collecting more black powder and old guns, so the list can change daily.


Contact me anytime via email with questions or comments. I am always open to offers or trades, and my prices can be flexible. Don't hesitate to contact me; the worst I can say is 'no'.



Regards,
   Thomas

title: For Sale:  Blast from the Past - Beretta Mod. 950BS in .25 ACP.
postcontent: Beretta Mod. 950BS in .25 ACP - Private sale of an older classic Beretta in very good condition.  Made in Italy.  When I called Beretta, they advised the gun's serial number predates their record keeping, and that based upon its features it had to have been manufactured sometime between 1950 and 1959.  Bore is in excellent shape.  I don't think it was shot much, as the magazine release wasn't working right (actually the problem was with the magazine).  10 seconds of dremel work to the magazine only, and now she functions perfectly.  Has a tip up barrel.  Perfect gun for someone that is disabled, or has difficulty racking a slide (elderly, those with arthritis, small women etc...).  You never rack the slide to shot this gun.  You just drop a round in the tip up barrel, and once fired, it automatically cycles the next round.  For a “mouse” gun, it has a large 8+1 capacity.  Taurus also makes a small caliber tip barrel design, but has a much heavier trigger (due to being double action).  The Beretta is only single action, (where the hammer resets due to the blowback from the fired cartridge, and not from pulling the trigger – The trigger only releases the hammer, which equals a light and smooth trigger).  Very nice aged look.  It looks much better than the photos indicate (horrible contrast and hard light).  Nice, and small for concealed carry.  Carry it with Hornady “magic” bullets, and it will be just as effective as a 40 caliber. I already have two (2) good shooting .25 acp caliber guns, and can't really justify keeping this one.  Own a classic Beretta for only $235. Private sale.   Must be over 21, have a Florida D/L and be legally able to own a firearm.  Sale will must take place at my office in Palm Harbor.  Don't waste my time if you are not willing to sign a bill of sale, or won't allow me to make a copy of your Florida d/license.  If you want to spend a little less, I am willing to keep the Beretta, and would sell one of my Ravens that is in like new condition (with box), with only about 150 rds through it for $140.00.  I never had any type of malfunction/misfire with the Raven.
